          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a246********56bb</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********KfL1</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-hakonosland-projects/24b1d262-114e-4e39-90c6-3be0e3a37b5b/tasks/a2464e204c0e756bb.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Review bash scripts quality\" completed</summary>\n<result>I now have a complete picture of all the moving parts. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: mjolnir.sh, mjolnir-watchdog.sh, install.sh\n\n---\n\n### CRITICAL Issues\n\n---\n\n**[CRITICAL] Temp file not cleaned up on rate-limit retry — result file leaked**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:185`\n\nWhen `run_agent` detects a rate limit, it calls itself recursively. The original `$result_file` temp file is never deleted before the recursive call returns. In a long run with many retries, this leaks `/tmp/mjolnir-result-*.json` files. More importantly, if `mktemp` or the recursive call fails, the original temp file is left behind permanently (the `rm -f` at line 203/208 only runs on the non-rate-limit path).\n\n```bash\n# Current: temp file created at line 155, but on the rate-limit path:\nif [[ \"$rate_limited\" == \"True\" ]]; then\n    ...\n    run_agent \"$role\" ...   # recursive — original $result_file is NEVER rm'd\n    return $?\nfi\n# rm -f \"$result_file\" never reached in the rate-limit branch\n```\n\nFix: add `rm -f \"$result_file\"` before the recursive call:\n\n```bash\nif [[ \"$rate_limited\" == \"True\" ]]; then\n    rm -f \"$result_file\"\n    check_and_wait_rate_limit\n    run_agent \"$role\" \"$system_prompt_file\" \"$user_prompt\" \"$budget\" \"$work_dir\"\n    return $?\nfi\n```\n\n---\n\n**[CRITICAL] Unchecked `parse_stream.py` exit code silently swallows pipeline errors**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:169`\n\n```bash\necho \"$user_prompt\" | claude -p \\\n    ... \\\n    2>/dev/null | python3 \"${LIB_DIR}/parse_stream.py\" > \"$result_file\" || true\n```\n\nThe `|| true` suppresses all pipeline failures. `parse_stream.py` exits with code 1 when `result[\"error\"]` is true (line 116 of parse_stream.py), but that exit code is thrown away here. Worse: if `claude` is not installed, crashes, or outputs nothing, `parse_stream.py` writes an empty/default JSON object to `$result_file`. The orchestrator then reads `rate_limited: False` and `error: False` from that default object, treating a total failure as a success. The agent proceeds to the evaluate step with no work done.\n\nWith `set -euo pipefail` active in the script, a pipeline failure would normally abort — but `|| true` intentionally overrides this on the exact line that matters most.\n\nFix: remove `|| true`, handle the non-zero exit explicitly, and verify `$result_file` is non-empty and valid JSON before reading it:\n\n```bash\nif ! echo \"$user_prompt\" | claude -p ... | python3 \"${LIB_DIR}/parse_stream.py\" > \"$result_file\"; then\n    local stream_exit=$?\n    # only treat as hard error if the result file is missing or empty\n    [[ -s \"$result_file\" ]] || { rm -f \"$result_file\"; return 1; }\nfi\n```\n\n---\n\n**[CRITICAL] Shell injection in `read_config` via Python heredoc — `$1` is unquoted inside Python string**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:50`\n\n```python\nkeys = '$1'.split('.')\n```\n\n`$1` inside the Python string is expanded by the shell before Python sees it. If the TOML key path contains shell metacharacters (e.g., a backtick or `$(...)` in a project.toml field), this would execute arbitrary commands. While the call sites are all hardcoded strings today (lines 62–71), this is a latent injection surface. The same pattern applies to `${PROJECT_DIR}` and `${LOG_FILE}` interpolated directly into Python source strings throughout the file.\n\nFix: pass values as arguments, not via string interpolation into Python source:\n\n```bash\nread_config() {\n    python3 - \"$1\" \"$2\" \"${PROJECT_DIR}/project.toml\" <<'EOF'\nimport sys, json\ntry:\n    import tomllib\nexcept ImportError:\n    import tomli as tomllib\nkey_path, default, config_file = sys.argv[1], sys.argv[2], sys.argv[3]\nwith open(config_file, 'rb') as f:\n    config = tomllib.load(f)\nkeys = key_path.split('.')\nval = config\nfor k in keys:\n    val = val.get(k) if isinstance(val, dict) else None\n    if val is None:\n        print(default)\n        sys.exit(0)\nprint('\\n'.join(str(v) for v in val) if isinstance(val, list) else val)\nEOF\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### HIGH Issues\n\n---\n\n**[HIGH] Infinite recursion in `run_agent` on persistent rate limits**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:185`\n\n`run_agent` calls itself unconditionally after a rate limit wait. If the API returns another rate limit event immediately (e.g., usage cap rather than a temporary limit), this recurses forever until the stack overflows. Bash has a default recursion limit (~1000 levels), after which the script crashes with an unclear error rather than halting cleanly.\n\nFix: add a retry counter parameter or a local counter checked before recursing:\n\n```bash\nrun_agent() {\n    local role=\"$1\" system_prompt_file=\"$2\" user_prompt=\"$3\"\n    local budget=\"$4\" work_dir=\"${5:-${PROJECT_DIR}}\" retry=\"${6:-0}\"\n\n    if [[ \"$retry\" -ge 3 ]]; then\n        echo \"run_agent: too many rate-limit retries for ${role}\" >&2\n        return 1\n    fi\n    ...\n    run_agent \"$role\" \"$system_prompt_file\" \"$user_prompt\" \"$budget\" \"$work_dir\" $((retry + 1))\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**[HIGH] `attempt` loop counter is read from state on every outer iteration but not reset correctly after a sprint advances**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:426–503`\n\nWhen a sprint passes and the loop advances to the next sprint (line 501), `state_cmd transition generating sprint=\"$sprint\" attempt=0` sets attempt=0 in state. However, the local `attempt` variable is re-read from state at line 433 (`attempt=\"$(get_attempt)\"`) only at the top of the outer `while` loop. The inner loop starts with `attempt=$((attempt + 1))` at line 438. If the script restarts mid-sprint, it re-reads the correct attempt from state. But in normal (non-crash) operation across sprints, `attempt` is read once outside the inner loop at line 433 — so when the outer loop iterates, `get_attempt` correctly returns 0. This is fine. However, there is a subtler issue: after `state_cmd transition evaluating` at line 458, the phase changes to \"evaluating\". If the script crashes and restarts here, `get_phase` returns \"evaluating\", which is not \"idle\", \"planning\", or \"rate_limited\". The `main()` function falls through to the generate/evaluate loop with the correct sprint but skips re-running the generator — the evaluator runs again with no new generated output. The generator step for that attempt is silently skipped.\n\nFix: treat \"evaluating\" as a resumption signal that should re-run the generator for the current attempt, or save a `sub_phase` field to state before the generator and evaluator steps.\n\n---\n\n**[HIGH] `build_generator_prompt` and `build_evaluator_prompt` read `plan.md` and `eval_report.json` at prompt-build time without checking if those files exist**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:293, 322`\n\n`$(cat \"${PROJECT_DIR}/plan.md\")` inside a heredoc silently produces an empty string if `plan.md` is missing (e.g., on a crash-resume before the planner wrote the file). The generator then receives an empty build plan. The same applies to `rubric.md`. With `set -euo pipefail`, a failing `cat` inside a command substitution does not abort the script — command substitutions run in a subshell and their exit codes are not checked by the `-e` flag in that context.\n\nFix: guard reads explicitly:\n\n```bash\n[[ -f \"${PROJECT_DIR}/plan.md\" ]] || { echo \"Error: plan.md missing\" >&2; exit 1; }\n```\n\n---\n\n**[HIGH] Watchdog uses unquoted `${PROJECT_DIR}` in the tmux command — breaks on paths with spaces**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir-watchdog.sh:53`\n\n```bash\ntmux new-session -d -s \"$SESSION_NAME\" \\\n    \"bash ${SCRIPT_DIR}/mjolnir.sh ${PROJECT_DIR} 2>&1 | tee -a ${PROJECT_DIR}/mjolnir-tmux.log\"\n```\n\nThe entire command is passed as a single quoted string to tmux, but the variable expansions inside that string are not double-quoted. Any project directory path containing a space will break the command silently. The session will be created but the inner command will fail immediately.\n\nFix:\n\n```bash\ntmux new-session -d -s \"$SESSION_NAME\" \\\n    \"bash '${SCRIPT_DIR}/mjolnir.sh' '${PROJECT_DIR}' 2>&1 | tee -a '${PROJECT_DIR}/mjolnir-tmux.log'\"\n```\n\n---\n\n**[HIGH] `is_rate_limited` state command output parsed with two separate Python invocations — TOCTOU race**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:123–131`\n\n```bash\nrl_info=\"$(state_cmd is_rate_limited)\"\nis_limited=\"$(echo \"$rl_info\" | python3 -c \"... print(json.load(sys.stdin)['rate_limited'])\")\"\n...\nwait_secs=\"$(echo \"$rl_info\" | python3 -c \"... print(json.load(sys.stdin)['wait_seconds'])\")\"\n```\n\n`$rl_info` is already captured as a string so there is no state race, but spawning two separate Python processes to extract two fields from the same JSON string is fragile and wasteful. More critically: if `state_cmd is_rate_limited` outputs anything unexpected (a Python traceback, an extra warning line), both downstream parsers will silently produce wrong values and `is_limited` will be empty, causing the `[[ \"$is_limited\" == \"True\" ]]` check to pass through without waiting.\n\nFix: parse both fields in one invocation and output `is_limited wait_secs` as two lines, or use `jq`.\n\n---\n\n### MEDIUM Issues\n\n---\n\n**[MEDIUM] `count_sprints` falls back to `5` silently if `plan.md` is missing or has no sprint headings**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:257`\n\n```bash\ngrep -cE '^## Sprint [0-9]+' \"${PROJECT_DIR}/plan.md\" 2>/dev/null || echo \"5\"\n```\n\nIf the planner wrote a plan that uses different heading formatting (e.g., `### Sprint 1` or `## Sprint One`), the count will be 0, and the `|| echo \"5\"` fallback silently runs 5 sprints against a plan that may have none. This should be a hard error, not a fallback.\n\n---\n\n**[MEDIUM] `log_event` constructs JSON by embedding shell variables into Python source strings**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:76–91`\n\n```python\nentry = {'ts': time.strftime('%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S%z'), 'event': '$event'}\n```\n\n`$event` is expanded by the shell into a Python string literal. If the event name or any `key=value` argument contains a single quote, the Python code becomes a syntax error. The extra args are passed as `sys.argv` which is safe, but the `event` name itself is embedded raw.\n\n---\n\n**[MEDIUM] `install_playwright` sets `PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH=0` but this only affects the current install.sh subshell**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/install.sh:143`\n\n```bash\nexport PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH=0\n```\n\nThis export is visible only within the `install.sh` process. When `mjolnir.sh` later invokes `npx playwright` (via the evaluator agent), `PLAYWRIGHT_BROWSERS_PATH` is not set, so Playwright reverts to its default location and may not find the system Chromium on the Raspberry Pi. The variable needs to be set persistently (e.g., in `~/.bashrc` or via a wrapper script).\n\n---\n\n**[MEDIUM] `install_python_deps` checks `sys.version_info.minor` without checking the major version**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/install.sh:165`\n\n```bash\npython_minor=\"$(python3 -c 'import sys; print(sys.version_info.minor)')\"\nif [[ \"$python_minor\" -lt 11 ]]; then\n```\n\nOn Python 2 (unlikely but possible on old systems where `python3` is absent and a shim exists), or if a future Python 4 is released, the minor version check alone is incorrect. This is low risk in practice but the check should also validate `sys.version_info.major == 3`.\n\n---\n\n**[MEDIUM] `verify_install` in install.sh calls `$cmd --version` for every tool including `jq`, which uses `--version` correctly, but `tmux` outputs to stdout while others differ — not a crash, but `head -1` is fragile**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/install.sh:250`\n\n```bash\nversion=\"$($cmd --version 2>/dev/null | head -1 || echo 'OK')\"\n```\n\nThis is functional but `tmux -V` (not `--version`) is the correct flag for tmux; `tmux --version` works on newer versions but fails silently on older ones. The `|| echo 'OK'` masks this, so the version just shows \"OK\" rather than the actual version. Minor, but defeats the purpose of the verification step.\n\n---\n\n### LOW Issues\n\n---\n\n**[LOW] `get_phase`, `get_sprint`, `get_attempt`, `get_total_sprints` each spawn a separate Python process**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:103–117`\n\nThese four helpers are called sequentially in the main loop and at startup. Each spawns Python, loads JSON, and prints one field. A single `state_cmd read` call parsed once would be significantly faster and avoid four separate reads of `state.json` in quick succession.\n\n---\n\n**[LOW] `PROJECT_DIR` is resolved via `cd \"$1\" && pwd` which silently succeeds on symlinks**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:23`\n\nIf `$1` is a symlink to a directory, `cd ... && pwd` returns the symlink path on some systems and the physical path on others (depending on whether `cd -P` is used). This can cause mismatches between `$PROJECT_DIR` and paths constructed by the tmux session name in the watchdog. Minor inconsistency but worth standardizing with `cd -P`.\n\n---\n\n**[LOW] `SESSION_NAME` in watchdog includes only `basename` of the project dir**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir-watchdog.sh:19`\n\n```bash\nSESSION_NAME=\"mjolnir-$(basename \"$PROJECT_DIR\")\"\n```\n\nIf two projects share the same directory name (e.g., `workspace/client-a/my-app` and `workspace/client-b/my-app`), the watchdog for the second will see the first's tmux session as \"alive\" and never restart it. Use a hash or the full path digest as part of the session name.\n\n---\n\n**[LOW] `notify` in mjolnir.sh spawns a background Python process with no cleanup on exit**\n\nFile: `/Users/hakonosland/projects/mjolnir/mjolnir.sh:96`\n\n```bash\npython3 \"${LIB_DIR}/notify.py\" \"$message\" \"$level\" 2>/dev/null &\n```\n\nBackground processes are not reaped, leaving zombie processes if notify.py hangs (e.g., on a network timeout to ntfy.sh). A `wait` call at script exit or a timeout wrapper would be cleaner.\n\n---\n\n## Review Summary\n\n| Severity | Count | Status |\n|----------|-------|--------|\n| CRITICAL | 3     | block  |\n| HIGH     | 5     | warn   |\n| MEDIUM   | 4     | info   |\n| LOW      | 4     | note   |\n\n**Verdict: BLOCK — 3 CRITICAL issues must be fixed before this is used in production.**\n\nThe three critical issues are:\n\n1. **Temp file leak in `run_agent` rate-limit retry** — the `$result_file` from the original call is never cleaned up before the recursive call, and the cleanup path at the bottom of the function is unreachable in the rate-limit branch.\n\n2. **`|| true` on the Claude pipeline** — a total failure of the `claude` process produces a default \"success\" JSON object, causing the orchestrator to proceed silently with no work done and no error raised.\n\n3. **Shell injection surface in `read_config`** — `$1` (the TOML key path) and multiple `${PROJECT_DIR}` references are interpolated directly into Python source code strings. All call sites are currently safe, but this is one malformed `project.toml` or unusual path away from arbitrary code execution.\n\nThe five HIGH issues are all correctness problems: infinite recursion on persistent rate limits, silent skip of the generator on crash-resume during evaluation, missing guards for `plan.md` reads, path-with-spaces breakage in the watchdog's tmux command, and fragile two-invocation JSON parsing with no error handling.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>27326</total_tokens><tool_uses>6</tool_uses><duration_ms>105193</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-hakonosland-projects/24b1d262-114e-4e39-90c6-3be0e3a37b5b/tasks/a2464e204c0e756bb.output",
